.opencode/specs/deep-loops/035-gpt-reliability-fixes/plan-review/briefs/G8-regression-rollback.md:1:# Gap-Analysis Brief G8 — Regression risk & rollback/rollout gaps
.opencode/specs/deep-loops/035-gpt-reliability-fixes/plan-review/briefs/G8-regression-rollback.md:10:- The rollout/rollback story: 034's synthesis mentioned feature-flagged rollout + per-command opt-in as a GAP — does 035 actually incorporate it, or did the plan drop it? Is there a phase that owns the rollout mechanism, or is every phase expected to hand-roll its own flag?
.opencode/specs/deep-loops/035-gpt-reliability-fixes/plan-review/iterations/iter-005.md:16:`005-progress-records/spec.md:73` requires started/completed pairs "for any step expected >60s without another write." The benchmark watchdog at `033-deep-loop-behavior-benchmarks/001-framework-and-harness/spec.md:73` is 120s no-progress. The observed council stalls are 12.3m / 13.4m / 13.8m (`004-rollout-council-improvement/scorecard.md:18-20, 50`) and context stalls 4.3m / 4.5m (`003-rollout-research-context/scorecard.md:26, 66`). None of these reference 60s as a natural unit; 60s is half the watchdog, but the design (`iter-014.md:24`) and 005's spec give no rationale for the ratio. A 30s threshold or a 90s threshold would yield the same observable behavior at the cell level, and the value is unanchored. **Recommended amendment:** In REQ-001 or the design-fidelity notes, derive the threshold from the watchdog window (120s no-progress) and the minimum useful lead time, e.g. "started must be emitted no later than t = (watchdog_window − per-event_watchdog_safety_margin) / 2; with watchdog=120s the threshold is 60s." If the threshold is instead a usability floor, say so and cite a measured LLM sub-step latency distribution. Either way, the number should not be free-floating.
